✅ SOLID Refactor (Clean Architecture)

We move logic into a Service class

1. 🎯 Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)
Create a Service
app/Services/UserProfileService.php
✅ Service class
<?php

namespace App\Services;

use App\Models\User;

class UserProfileService
{
    public function update(User $user, array $data): User
    {
        $oldEmail = $user->email;

        $user->fill($data);

        // Business rule: email changed → reset verification
        if ($user->isDirty('email') && $oldEmail !== $data['email']) {
            $user->email_verified_at = null;
        }

        $user->save();

        return $user;
    }
}
2. 🎮 Controller becomes thin (GOOD)
use App\Services\UserProfileService;
use App\Http\Requests\ProfileUpdateRequest;

public function update(ProfileUpdateRequest $request, UserProfileService $service)
{
    $service->update(
        $request->user(),
        $request->validated()
    );

    return redirect()->route('profile.edit')
        ->with('status', 'profile-updated');
}
3. 🧠 Why this is SOLID
✔ S — Single Responsibility
Controller = HTTP only
Service = business logic
✔ O — Open/Closed Principle

You can extend behavior without modifying controller:

Example: add audit logging later

public function update(User $user, array $data)
{
    // log changes here
}
✔ L — Liskov Substitution

Service can be swapped later (e.g. API version, admin version)

✔ I — Interface Segregation (optional improvement)

You can make it even cleaner:

interface UserProfileServiceInterface
{
    public function update(User $user, array $data): User;
}

Then:

class UserProfileService implements UserProfileServiceInterface
✔ D — Dependency Inversion

Controller depends on abstraction:

public function update(
    ProfileUpdateRequest $request,
    UserProfileServiceInterface $service
)
🚀 Optional: Even better (Action Class pattern)

Instead of Service:

app/Actions/UpdateUserProfile.php
class UpdateUserProfile
{
    public function handle(User $user, array $data)
    {
        $user->fill($data);

        if ($user->isDirty('email')) {
            $user->email_verified_at = null;
        }

        $user->save();

        return $user;
    }
}

Controller:

public function update(ProfileUpdateRequest $request, UpdateUserProfile $action)
{
    $action->handle($request->user(), $request->validated());

    return back()->with('status', 'profile-updated');
}
